				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/blackle" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(673491); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=673491&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183371" alt="blackle" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=673491)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/blackle" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(673491); return false;" >blackle</a></span> <span class="odate time_1321575777 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 Nov 2011 00:22</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1308560">
									

<p>I think it would make a lot of sense if 096 is triggered when it's recognized as something with an ugly face. I imagine the poor sap who took the image looking at the four pixels and thinking to himself &quot;I wonder if that's some sort of monster?&quot; That means even if you randomly generated a 2x2 image with those exact colours, they would still lack the context of the mountain image, meaning if you extracted the four pixels and blocked everything else out, 096 wouldn't be affected.</p>
<p>Hurm, if you could isolate the four pixels and stop the trigger, and you can blot out the four pixels and stop the trigger&#8230;</p>
<p>Could that be special containment for images such as this? Keep the four pixels separate from the main, context image, and when you need to use the image for whatever reason, you join the two.</p>

							</div>

								
